<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="387" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1338,1509]" pageId="14" pageNumber="387">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,305,1374,1400]" pageId="14" pageNumber="387">Distribution.</emphasis>
Atlanto-Mediterranean (
<bibRefCitation author="Bellan-Santini, D. &amp; Ruffo, S." box="[586,924,1375,1401]" pageId="14" pageNumber="387" pagination="273 - 292" refId="ref18519" refString="Bellan-Santini, D. &amp; Ruffo, S. (2003) Biogeography of benthic marine amphipods in Mediterranean Sea. Biogeographia-The Journal of Integrative Biogeography, 24 (1), 273 - 292. https: // doi. org / 10.21426 / B 6110176" type="journal article" year="2003">Bellan-Santini &amp; Ruffo 2003</bibRefCitation>
). The species is reported in 
<collectingCountry box="[1245,1326,1375,1401]" name="Cyprus" pageId="14" pageNumber="387">Cyprus</collectingCountry>
(Vasiliko bay) for the first time. In Vasiliko Bay, it is considered as a rare species (FI: 2.38 %).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="387" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1338,1509]" pageId="14" pageNumber="387">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,252,1447,1473]" pageId="14" pageNumber="387">Ecology.</emphasis>
In Vasiliko Bay it was found at 
<quantity box="[582,635,1447,1473]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="387" unit="m" value="40.0">40 m</quantity>
depth in sandy substrate with 9.414 % organic matter, in association with the flora species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. V. Lamouroux" authorityYear="1809" baseAuthorityName="Forsskal" box="[336,458,1483,1509]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Caulerpaceae" genus="Caulerpa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bryopsidales" pageId="14" pageNumber="387" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="prolifera">
<emphasis box="[336,458,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="387">C. prolifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The station was in “moderate” ecological status according to the Bentix Index.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
